                <td rowspan="5" colspan="3" valign="top"> 
                  <div align="left"> 
                    <table width="100%" border="0" cellpadding="4">
                       <tr> 
                        <td height="63"><img src="../global/images/trans.gif" width="1" height="1"> 
                           <table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0"><tr><td bgcolor="#000000" height="8" width="100%" colspan="3"><span class="header">Mission Madness #1</span></td></tr><tr><td bgcolor="#333399" height="2" width="41%"><img src="/stccg/global/images/trek/glear.gif" width="1" height="5"></td><td height="2" width="1%"><img src="/stccg/global/images/trek/glear.gif" width="1" height="5"></td><td height="2" width="58%" bgcolor="#FF9C00"><img src="/stccg/global/images/trek/glear.gif" width="1" height="5"></td></tr></table><TABLE WIDTH="100%" CELLPADDING=5 BORDER=0><TR><TD VALIGN="TOP" COLSPAN=2><SPAN CLASS="header">Rating </SPAN><IMG SRC="/stccg/global/images/rating/9.gif" BORDER=0></TD></TR><TR><TD VALIGN="TOP"><A HREF="articleread.php3?article=21"><IMG SRC="/stccg/global/images/read.gif" BORDER=0></A></TD><TD><A HREF="articlereview.php3?article=21"><IMG SRC="/stccg/global/images/review.gif" BORDER=0></A></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif" size="5" COLOR="#FFFFFF">Author</Font></TD><TD><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2"><A HREF="../membercenter/directory/memberpage.php3?member=5538">Bart "Bartman" McLeroy</A></FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD VALIGN="TOP"><SPAN CLASS="header">Description</SPAN></TD><TD WIDTH="90%"><span class=text>In this multi-part article series I will explore missions that do more than provide points.</span></TD></TR><TR><TD VALIGN="TOP"><SPAN CLASS="header">Article</SPAN></TD><TD WIDTH="90%" ><span class=text>In this multi-part article series I will explore missions that do more than provide points.  With the Star Trek CCG becoming faster and more competitive, you need every advantage you can muster.  The player that can critically examine his mission selection can help tilt that advantage in his favor.<br>
<br>
The first class of missions examined will be those that give you something extra when solved.  Establish Relations allows you to download any Non-Aligned personnel to the mission when it is solved.  Not only do you get your pick of personnel, regardless of their native Quadrant, they go straight to the mission and join your away team.  This can be especially powerful if you lost key personnel in your mission attempt and need to replenish your skill base.  <br>
<br>
Similarly, Runabout Search lets the solving player download Odo or Quark to the mission.  While not as versatile as the download at Establish Relations, both Odo and Quark are valuable personnel that should find a place in many crews and away teams.  Note that you cannot download &quot;any&quot; Odo or Quark - this limits you to Quark from RoA, Odo from DS9, or Odo from TwT.  Fortunately this last Odo is Non-Aligned, opening this mission up to more affiliations.  He&#146;s an especially welcome addition to an [OS] Federation crew operating in the normal universe.<br>
<br>
Construct Depot has been a staple of Dominion decks for quite a while.  One reason is safety - it can only be attempted by the player who seeded it.  Another equally important reason is that when you solve the mission, you can download a Remote Supply Depot to the mission.  With the release of Blaze of Glory this special ability became less potent.  With Ultimatum, you don&#146;t need to solve the mission to download a RSD, and you can download two free equipment cards as well.  Still, Construct Depot remains a valuable mission with a valuable download.<br>
<br>
Colony Preparations has a similarly valuable attribute.  When you solve this mission, you may download a Colony to that location.  Colony has been a favorite source of bonus points since its release.  The Wake of the Borg dampened its popularity somewhat, and it has no built-in reporting abilities.  Given its ability to quickly create points from personnel cards that you already brought to the mission, it is a worthwhile but rather overlooked mission.<br>
<br>
Mineral Survey has a unique bonus built in.  When solved, the solving player may draw up to two cards.  Drawing extra cards is always nice, especially when it can&#146;t be cancelled (unlike Kivas Fajo: Collector).  If you work this into a Blood Oath deck, solving the mission could result in a download of some key personnel or ships.<br>
<br>
Plague Planet was one of the first missions released with bonus text, and that bonus remains fairly unique.  If you solve the mission, you automatically overcome Tarellian Plague Ships.  If your opponent solves your Plague Planet, Plague Ships are worth no points if overcome.  The value of this mission is obvious, but its practicality waxes and wanes with the popularity of the Tarellian Plague Ship dilemma.  After the DS9 expansion was released, the Aphasia Device - Tarellian Plague Ship combo became widespread.  With TPS gaining new life in the form of an Enhanced Premiere Combo dilemma, this mission may see more use.  A player who has solved Plague Planet and has Dr. McCoy in play is immune to a large variety of dilemma combos.<br>
<br>
The last two missions examined in this article have similar special attributes and can be combined with powerful results.  The player who solves Mine Dilithium, the ubiquitous Mirror Quadrant mission, gets +1 to the range of all his ships.  Similarly, Test Propulsion Systems gives a +2 range bonus to its solving player&#146;s ships.  Test Propulsion Systems is universal and its effect is cumulative, so a player with a few of these in his deck may end up with some incredibly well ranged ships.<br>
<br>
Next time I will tackle missions with variable point values, and how they can work for you.  See you then!<br>
<br>
Missions reviewed in this article:<br>
<br>
Establish Relations (Universal, Alpha Quadrant, Planet, OTSD)<br>
<br>
Runabout Search (Unique, Alpha Quadrant, Space/Planet, RoA)<br>
<br>
Construct Depot (Universal, Alpha Quadrant, Space, Dom)<br>
<br>
Colony Preparations (Universal, Gamma Quadrant, Planet, DS9)<br>
<br>
Mineral Survey (Universal, Alpha Quadrant, Planet, OTSD)<br>
<br>
Plague Planet (Unique, Alpha Quadrant, Planet, QC)<br>
<br>
Mine Dilithium (Unique, Mirror Quadrant, Planet, MM)<br>
<br>
Test Propulsion Systems (Universal, Alpha Quadrant, Space, OTSD) </span></TD></TR><TR><TD VALIGN="TOP"><A HREF="articleread.php3?article=21"><IMG SRC="/stccg/global/images/read.gif" BORDER=0></A></TD><TD><A HREF="articlereview.php3?article=21"><IMG SRC="/stccg/global/images/review.gif" BORDER=0></A></TD></TR><TR><TD VALIGN="TOP"><a href="articles.php3"><img src="/stccg/global/images/back.gif" border="0" ></a></TD><TD><a href="articleprint.php3?article=21" TARGET="BLANK_"><img src="/stccg/global/images/print.gif" border="0"></a></TD></TR></TABLE>
